48
05:00.180 --> 05:06.210
or a description of a molecule or really anything else we have in mind, and there's some computational task

49
05:06.210 --> 05:10.830
being performed on that input alone.

50
05:10.830 --> 05:19.560
The key point here is
that the entire input is provided to the computation, and nothing about the
input is hidden from it.

51
05:19.560 --> 05:23.970
The query model of
computation works differently.

52
05:23.970 --> 05:31.620
In the query model, the input is made available
in the form of a function which the computation can
access by making queries,

53
05:31.620 --> 05:36.690
or in other words, by evaluating the function
on different inputs.

54
05:36.690 --> 05:40.320
Here you can see that represented
in the form of a picture.

55
05:40.320 --> 05:46.830
Similar to what we had before, the computation is represented
by a blue rectangle, but instead of receiving an input directly

56
05:46.830 --> 05:55.980
in the form of a string
of bits, for instance, it accesses the input by effectively asking questions
and receiving answers.

57
05:55.980 --> 06:03.330
We sometimes use the
terms oracle and black box to refer to the mechanism
that provides the input.

58
06:03.330 --> 06:11.910
There is a distinction between
an oracle and a black box in complexity theory, but that won't be relevant at all for the purposes of this discussion.

59
06:11.910 --> 06:16.950
Anyway, these terms are meant
to convey the basic idea.

60
06:16.950 --> 06:24.630
In ancient Greece, you
could go to an oracle, like the Oracle at Delphi,
and ask an important question,

61
06:24.630 --> 06:33.000
and the oracle would answer
that specific question, but she certainly wouldn't tell you everything that she knew.

62
06:33.000 --> 06:39.420
Along similar lines, when
we think about a black box, we have in mind some
sort of process or system

63
06:39.420 --> 06:47.340
where we can choose what goes in and we can see what comes out, but we don't have any understanding
of its inner workings.

64
06:47.340 --> 06:56.010
And that's the case here. The input to the problem
takes the form of a function, and all that we can do is
to evaluate that function,

65
06:56.010 --> 07:01.080
but otherwise, we don't have
any knowledge or understanding of how it works.

66
07:01.080 --> 07:07.650
Throughout the lesson,
we'll reserve the letter f for the function that
represents the input, and we'll make the assumption

67
07:07.650 --> 07:11.550
that it always takes the
form that you see right here.

68
07:11.550 --> 07:17.850
Sigma denotes the binary alphabet, so f is a function from strings
of bits to strings of bits,

69
07:17.850 --> 07:26.100
and specifically, we'll
assume that the input to f is a string of bits having length n, and the output is a string
of bits having length m,

70
07:26.100 --> 07:30.150
where n and m are positive integers.

71
07:30.150 --> 07:39.480
For different problems, we'll
have restrictions on n and m, but in all cases, the input function will
take a form like this.

72
07:39.480 --> 07:47.700
When we say that a
computation makes a query, what we mean is that the
function f is evaluated once,

73
07:47.700 --> 07:55.590
that is, some string x of length N is selected by the computation, and the string f of x is
then made available to it

74
07:55.590 --> 08:02.220
by the oracle or the black box. And finally, the very simple way that we'll measure the computational cost

75
08:02.220 --> 08:06.630
of a query algorithm is to count how many queries it requires.

76
08:06.630 --> 08:13.290
So, although it is true that
we are really most interested in how long computations take, when we study the query model,

77
08:13.290 --> 08:20.190
we generally keep things
simple and just count queries, and that's what we will do in this lesson.

78
08:20.190 --> 08:26.850
Now, let's take a look at a
few examples of query problems, meaning computational
problems in the query model,

79
08:26.850 --> 08:35.910
and here, by the way, I'm just gonna describe
the problems themselves, and at this point, I won't say anything
about how to solve them.

80
08:35.910 --> 08:39.420
The first problem is the OR problem.

81
08:39.420 --> 08:46.110
In this case, the input is a function
from n bits to just 1 bit, so m is equal to 1 for this problem,

82
08:46.110 --> 08:50.640
and the required output for
the problem is either 1 or 0.

83
08:50.640 --> 08:57.570
If there is some n bits string x for which f of x is equal to 1, then the correct answer is 1,

84
08:57.570 --> 09:04.470
and otherwise, if f of x is
always 0 for every string x, then the correct answer is 0.

85
09:04.470 --> 09:12.690
So if we think about the function f as providing us with random
access to two to the n bits, one for each n bit string x,

86
09:12.690 --> 09:20.760
then what the it's asking
for is the OR of those bits, and that's why it's called the OR problem.

87
09:20.760 --> 09:27.360
Another example is the parity problem, which is similar to the OR problem except that asks for the parity,

88
09:27.360 --> 09:34.470
or in other words, the eXclusive OR of all of the single-bit
output values of the function.

89
09:34.470 --> 09:43.260
Another way to say that is
that the correct answer is 0 if the number of n bits strings x for which f of x is equal to 1 is even,

90
09:43.260 --> 09:48.570
and the correct answer is
1 if that number is odd.

91
09:48.570 --> 09:54.390
An example of a problem where m is not necessarily equal to 1 is the minimum problem.

92
09:54.390 --> 10:00.840
Here, the function f takes the usual form, and there are no restrictions on n and m,

93
10:00.840 --> 10:07.680
and the correct answer is whatever output value
of the function comes first in the lexicographic
or dictionary ordering

94
10:07.680 --> 10:16.680
of binary strings. Alternatively, if you wanna
think about strings of length m as representing non-negative
integers in binary notation,

95
10:16.680 --> 10:25.080
then the correct answer
is the smallest possible or minimum value that
comes out of this function.

